      "\nLet's write the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Aesop\n\nset_option aesop.check.all true\n\n@[ext]\nstructure MyProd (α β : Type _) where\n  fst : α\n  snd : β\n\nvariable {α β γ δ ι: Type}\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α β} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · ext : 1\n      · sorry\n      · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α (MyProd β γ)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd (α → β) γ} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · ext x x_1 : 2\n      sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : (α → β) × (γ → δ → ι)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (erase Aesop.BuiltinRules.destructProducts)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n```\n\nThe problem asks us to complete the proof for the case `p = q` where `p` and `q` are of type `(α → β) × (γ → δ → ι)`. The goal is to show `p = q`.\n\nLet's think about how to prove this. If `p` and `q` are products, then `p = q` means both components are equal. So we need to show:\n1. `p.1 = q.1` (equality of first components)\n2. `p.2 = q.2` (equality of second components)\n\nThe `ext` tactic is used for function extensionality. When applied to products, it will generate goals for each component. Let's apply `ext`:\n\n```tactics\nimport Aesop\n\nset_option aesop.check.all true\n\n@[ext]\nstructure MyProd (α β : Type _) where\n  fst : α\n  snd : β\n\nvariable {α β γ δ ι: Type}\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α β} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · ext : 1\n      · sorry\n      · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α (MyProd β γ)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd (α → β) γ} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · ext x x_1 : 2\n      sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : (α → β) × (γ → δ → ι)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (erase Aesop.BuiltinRules.destructProducts)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n```\n\nThe `aesop?` tactic is attempting to solve the goal using a combination of extensionality and other automated reasoning. The `(erase Aesop.BuiltinRules.destructProducts)` is preventing Aesop from using rules that would break down the product structure, which is likely not what we want as we need to prove equality of the whole product.\n\nThe problem arises in the last example, where `p` and `q` are of type `(α → β) × (γ → δ → ι)`. The `aesop?` tactic is generating subgoals for each component. The first subgoal is to prove equality of the first components, i.e., `p.1 = q.1`. The `ext` tactic is then used to introduce an arbitrary element `x` of the domain `α`, and the goal becomes `p.1 x = q.1 x`.\n\nSince `p.1` and `q.1` are functions of type `α → β`, we need to show that they are equal as functions. The equality of functions is typically proven by showing they have the same output for all inputs. The `ext x` introduces an arbitrary `x : α`, and the goal becomes `p.1 x = q.1 x`.\n\nAt this point, we have `p = q` as a hypothesis. Since `p` and `q` are products, `p.1` is the first component of `p`, and `q.1` is the first component of `q`. If `p = q`, then their components must be equal, so `p.1 x = q.1 x` should be true by reflexivity.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Aesop\n\nset_option aesop.check.all true\n\n@[ext]\nstructure MyProd (α β : Type _) where\n  fst : α\n  snd : β\n\nvariable {α β γ δ ι: Type}\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α β} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · sorry\n    · ext : 1\n      · sorry\n      · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd α (MyProd β γ)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd (α → β) γ} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    · ext x : 1\n      sorry\n    · ext x x